A1  - Aprami T.M. 
Y1  - 2024//
N2  - Background: Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is the most common endocrine disease among women of reproductive age-. It affects 6-10% of women of reproductive age worldwide and is a common cause of infertility. Women with PCOS are known to be at increased risk of dyslipidemia, hypertension, glucose intolerance, type 2 diabetes and metabolic syndrome. These factors are considered classic risk factors for the development of cardiovascular diseases. A number of researches have been done to assess the risk factors of hypertension in PCOS patients with inconclusive results. Aim(s): The exact risk factors and mechanisms regarding hypertension in women with PCOS are limited and unclear. The aim of this review is to summarize comprehensively the current knowledge on the risk factors of hypertension in women with PCOS. Material(s) and Method(s): Literature search was performed through PubMed, ScienceDirect, Cochrane Library, and Google Scholar (up to December 2023). All relevant articles published in English language were identified and reviewed using Centre for Evidence-based Medicine (CEBM) critical appraisal tool to prevent bias [1-5]. Result(s): Data collected from patients in three retrospective study and two cross sectional study. All the reports investigate the risk of cardiovascular diseases including hypertension in women with PCOS. The results of the five studies observed PCOS women had higher risk of developing metabolic disorders, including hypertension, obesity, dyslipidemia, insulin resistance and diabetes mellitus. Furthermore, hyperandrogenaemia is associated with elevated blood pressure independent of the patient's age, insulin resistance, obesity and dyslipidemia. Conclusion(s): Available studies show that women with PCOS more frequently have increased cardiovascular risk factors, including hypertension. Patients with PCOS should be screened for these diseases and educated about the lifestyle modifications that could prevent hypertension later in life.
