37. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase Weekly Updates
AN  - 639672589
T1  - Lifestyle management in polycystic ovary syndrome-Beyond diet and physical activity
T3  - International Congress on Obesity, ICO 2022. Melbourne, SA Australia.
A1  - Cowan S.
A1  - Lim S.
A1  - Alycia C.
A1  - Pirotta S.
A1  - Thomson R.
A1  - Gibson-Helm M.
A1  - Blackmore R.
A1  - Naderpoor N.
A1  - Bennett C.
A1  - Ee C.
A1  - Rao V.
A1  - Mousa A.
A1  - Alesi S.
A1  - Moran L. 
Y1  - 2022//
N2  - INTRODUCTION: Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is a common condition affecting reproductive-aged women with reproductive, metabolic, and psychological consequences. While weight and lifestyle management are first-line therapy in international evidence-based guidelines for PCOS, there is growing interest and research in the potential benefit of including psychological and sleep interventions, as well as a range of traditional, complimentary, and integrative medicine (TCIM) approaches, for optimal PCOS management. MATERIALS AND METHODS: This narrative review provides an overview of all relevant studies known to the authors investigating the effects of lifestyle, psychological, sleep, and TCIM interventions in PCOS. RESULT(S): There is limited evidence to recommend a specific diet composition for PCOS with approaches including modifying protein, carbohydrate, or fat generally having similar results. Promising evidence supports the provision of vigorous aerobic exercise, which can improve anthropometry, cardiorespiratory fitness and insulin resistance. Psychological and sleep interventions are important considerations, with women displaying poor emotional wellbeing and higher rates of sleep disturbance, limiting their ability to make positive lifestyle change. While optimizing sleep and emotional wellbeing may aid symptom management in PCOS, research exploring the efficacy of clinical interventions is lacking. Uptake of TCIM approaches, in particular supplement and herbal medicine use, by women with PCOS is growing. However, there is currently insufficient evidence to support integration into routine clinical practice. Meta-analyses investigating inositol supplementation have produced the most promising findings, showing improved metabolic profiles and reduced hyperan-drogenism. Findings from emerging evidence for other supplements, herbal medicines, acupuncture, and yoga is so far inconsistent, and to reduce heterogeneity more research in specific PCOS populations (e.g., defined age and BMI ranges) and consistent approaches to intervention delivery, duration, and comparators are needed. CONCLUSION(S): While there are a range of lifestyle components in addition to population-recommendations for diet and physical activity of potential benefit in PCOS, robust clinical trials are warranted to expand the relatively limited evidence-base regarding the provision of holistic management in PCOS. With consumer interest in holistic healthcare rising, healthcare providers will be required to broaden their knowledge pertaining to how these therapies can be safely and appropriately utilized as adjuncts to conventional medical management.
