A1  - Watanabe M. 
Y1  - 2024//
N2  - Introduction: Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is a common endocrine disorder of women in fertile age, presenting with anovulatory oligomenorrhea, hyperandrogenism and polycystic ovaries, frequently associated with metabolic syndrome. Causal treatment is not available, with guidelines suggesting lifestyle modification as the first therapeutic approach. The ketogenic diet (KD) is effective in the short-term treatment of several metabolic conditions. Some studies suggest that there may be a role for PCOS, although mostly very low-calorie approaches in obesity were leveraged, and only short-term evaluations are available. We therefore aimed to assess the persistence of the effect of an isocaloric or mildly hypocaloric KD in patients with PCOS and normal or excess weight. Method(s): Eighteen patients with PCOS and either oligomenorrhea or amenorrhea were enrolled. The patient demographics were as follows: 28% with normal weight, 28% with overweight, and 44% with obesity. All participants followed a ketogenic diet (KD) without meal replacements for 45 days. After this period, legumes and fruit were reintroduced as sources of carbohydrates for 45 more days, and thereafter healthy eating indications were given to the patient. Twelve of the enrolled patients completed the study. The patients were assessed before starting the diet and after 6 months. Anthropometric data (weight, BMI, waist circumference), body composition (DEXA), pelvic ultrasound, blood chemistry, hirsutism and menstrual cycles frequency were recorded. Result(s): Significant improvements were observed in weight loss, waist and hip circumferences, and body fat percentage after six months of dietary intervention. Menstrual cycles and ovarian volume improved independently of weight or fat loss. Sexual hormones like FSH, LH, and Progesterone showed significant changes that were not dependent on weight or fat loss. However, testosterone levels and hirsutism improvements were influenced by weight and fat mass reduction, suggesting that anthropometric and glucometabolic improvement may be the main drivers of hyperandrogenism amelioration. The study reported good tolerability and no significant adverse events, suggesting that the dietary intervention was both effective and safe for managing PCOS symptoms. Conclusion(s): our study showed that KD in PCOS exerts beneficial effects in the medium term, even in women with normal weight. This is mostly independent of body weight loss, suggesting that nutritional ketosis, beyond weight loss per se, improves ovarian function, probably reducing low grade inflammation and ovarian cells apoptosis. Moreover, not leveraging meal replacements represent a cost-effective alternative to commonly used very low-calorie approaches, with comparable results. .
