73. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2030109066
T1  - 151. Utilization of Lifestyle Medicine Referrals and Anti-Obesity Medications Over a 3-Year Period in an Adolescent Medicine Clinic
T3  - SAHM 2024. San Diego United States.
A1  - Kinsella E.
A1  - Sheeder J.
A1  - Batt C. 
Y1  - 2024//
N2  - Purpose: Obesity (body mass index;BMI>=95th percentile for age and sex) is common among adolescents; approximately 22% of US 12-to-19-year-olds experience obesity. Obesity is associated with increased morbidity and mortality in adulthood related to conditions like polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS), pre-diabetes and Type-2 diabetes, hypertension, hyperlipidemia, and fatty liver disease. In January 2023, the AAP introduced guidelines for the management of obesity in children and adolescents, ultimately recommending consideration of advanced therapies including medications earlier in the course of treatment than previously recommended. Specifically, Key Action Statement 12 recommends that providers offer weight loss pharmacotherapy to adolescents 12 years and older with obesity. The purpose of this study is to describe how Adolescent Medicine primary care providers managed obesity over the last three years by assessing referrals to weight management clinics and prescriptions for anti-obesity medications. Method(s): We performed a retrospective observational cohort study of patients aged 10-25 years seen in an Adolescent Medicine Clinic for a well-visit between July 2020 and June 2023 who have a BMI >=95th%ile or BMI >=30. We collected basic demographics (race/ethnicity, legal sex, insurance (public vs private)), referrals to Lifestyle Medicine (LM)/weight management clinic, and prescription of anti-obesity medications (AOM's). We compared patients referred to LM vs not and those prescribed AOM's vs not. This study was approved by the Colorado Multiple Institutional Review Board. Result(s): 1,760 patients were included; 60% were female, median age:16.3 (range 10-25 years). Median BMI 33.5/98th%ile. 73% were publicly insured. 165 patients (9.4%) were referred to Lifestyle Medicine, and 47 patients (2.7%) were prescribed anti-obesity medications. Groups were similar in age (p>0.1). Patients referred to LM had a higher BMI (38.2 (27.0-68.0) vs 33.2 (24.5-75.5);p<0.001). Patients prescribed AOM's had a higher BMI (40.1 (29.1-69.0) vs 33.4 (24.5-75.5);p<0.001). Those prescribed AOM's were more likely to be female than those who were not (83.0% vs 59.1%, p=0.004). Those were prescribed AOM's were more likely to be referred to LM than those who were not prescribed AOM's (23.4% vs 9.0%;p<0.001), and those who were referred to LM were more likely to be prescribed AOM's than those were not referred (6.7% vs 2.3%;p<0.001). Conclusion(s): A small minority of patients who meet BMI criteria for obesity are referred to lifestyle medicine or prescribed anti-obesity medications. Providers may be more likely to refer to LM for adolescents with higher BMI's and be more likely to prescribe AOM's to females. Limitations of this study include lack of data regarding patient preferences for AOM's and LM referrals, lack of data regarding provider training, comfort, and beliefs in managing obesity, and lack of longitudinal data to characterize trends over time. Based on rates of referrals to LM and rates of prescriptions for AOM's, there is significant discrepancy between current practice patterns and what is recommended by the 2023 AAP obesity management guidelines. Sources of Support: Children's Colorado, Section of Adolescent Medicine Research Funds.Copyright © 2023
