141. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2027606488
T1  - LIMITED ADOPTION OF CURRENT POLYCYSTIC OVARY SYNDROME (PCOS) RELATED INFERTILITY TREATMENT GUIDELINES BY REPRODUCTIVE ENDOCRINOLOGY AND INFERTILITY (REI) SPECIALISTS IN THE UNITED STATES (U.S.)
T3  - 79th Scientific Congress of the American Society for Reproductive Medicine. New Orleans United States.
A1  - Kim A.E.
A1  - Lee I.T.
A1  - Dokras A. 
Y1  - 2023//
N2  - OBJECTIVE: The 2018international guidelines recommend evidence-based practices for the management of PCOS-related infertility. To determine if these guidelines have been successfully implemented, we surveyed REI specialists in the U.S. MATERIALS AND METHODS: In 2022, we conducted an online survey of REIs and obtained demographic information, practice characteristics and fertility-related practice patterns related to PCOS patients. Logistic regression was performed to identify factors associated with use of letrozole as a first-line ovulation induction (OI) agent. RESULT(S): The demographics and practice data for 170 respondents (response rate 43%) are shown in the Table. Lifestyle changes were recommended by 77.7% respondents. More REIs reported using clomiphene citrate (CC) alone (21.8%, maximum dose 150-200mg) or CC+metformin (31.2%) compared to letrozole alone (18.8%, maximum dose 7.5-10mg) or letrozole+metformin (13.5%) as first-line agents for OI (p<0.001). The majority of physicians (66%) did not restrict use of metformin to patients with BMI>30. Only 8.8% used metformin alone as first-line treatment; 39.4% added metformin only if CC or letrozole failed to induce ovulation. Years in practice and physician age were significantly associated with use of letrozole alone and with metformin. Holding years in practice constant, older age was independently associated with less use of letrozole (45-54yrs aOR 0.25, 95% CI 0.11-0.61; >=55yrs aOR 0.20, 95% CI 0.09-0.48; reference group 30-44yrs). Most physicians (92.9%) recommended 3-6 ovulatory cycles before second-line therapy and about 40% routinely prescribed hCG trigger. If oral agents did not induce ovulation, 40.9% used gonadotropins, 37.6% recommended IVF, and 6.5% recommended ovarian drilling as next steps. CONCLUSION(S): Although letrozole is the recommended first line therapy for OI, our study highlights variations in management of PCOS-related infertility among REI providers in the U.S. Increased physician education in conjunction with widespread dissemination of guidelines is needed to standardize care and optimize outcomes. IMPACT STATEMENT: This study provides evidence for suboptimal guideline-directed therapy for first line treatment of PCOS related infertility. In-depth interviews may help understand barriers to adopting evidence-based guidelines in all age groups. [Formula presented] SUPPORT: NoneCopyright © 2023
