184. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 641024685
T1  - Is a Diagnosis of PCOS Worse Than a Diagnosis of Heart Disease, Diabetes or Breast Cancer?
T3  - 70th Annual Meeting of the Society for Reproductive Investigation, SRI 2023. Brisbane, QLD Australia.
A1  - Singh B.
A1  - Rempert A.
A1  - Sarria I.
A1  - Standeven L.
A1  - Nylander E.
A1  - Segars J. 
Y1  - 2023//
N2  - Introduction: While polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS) is one of the most common hormonal endocrine disorders among women of reproductive age, the psychosocial impact of polycystic ovarian syndrome has not been evaluated across different quality of life indicators and compared to other chronic conditions. In this review, we rigorously analyzed available evidence pertaining to the psychosocial burden of polycystic ovarian syndrome in women of reproductive age and compared validated quality of life scores of women with and without PCOS and before and after treatment. Method(s): We searched PubMed, PsychINFO, Embase, and Cochrane library for publications focused on polycystic ovary syndrome and quality of life. Only English-language publications that evaluated the association between diagnosed PCOS and QoL were included. The studies had to include standardized and validated quantitate questionnaires at baseline and after treatment. The articles were assessed for risk of bias using Newcastle-Ottawa scale. Result(s): A search of the 4 electronic databases resulted in a total of 4,212 peer-reviewed articles. After duplicates were removed (n=1182), 180 articles underwent title and abstract screening for relevancy. Irrelevant studies were removed (n=114), thus leaving 66 papers to undergo full text evaluation. Ultimately, 33 papers were included in the study 19 of 33 were observational cohort studies and the remaining 14 were RCTs. Short Form-36 was utilized by 11 articles 6 studies and 5 trials and consistently showed reduced scores in numerous domains among women with PCOS. In SF-36's general health, vitality, social functioning, and emotional role domains, PCOS scores were signifcantly lower than heart disease and diabetes mellitus Twelve articles used the Polycystic Ovary Syndrome Questionnaire (PCOSQ) and found statistically signifcant impairment of QoL in women diagnosed with PCOS across all domains. Six clinical trials reported improvement in improvement in PCOS-QoL symptoms severity score after treatment including therapy, lifestyle modification, medication, and a holistic yoga program. Conclusion(s): A diagnosis of polycystic ovarian syndrome often correlated with a disability score equal to or exceeding a diagnosis of heart disease, diabetes mellitus, and breast cancer. QoL scores were impaired at baseline but showed improvement after treatment. Patients were often associated with signifcant health disabilities such as physical pain, mental health struggles, fertility difculties, obesity, dissatisfaction with sex life, and diminished social function.
