275. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2018724375
T1  - 007 Pharmacological treatment of PCOS in adolescence
T3  - EBCOG 2021. Athens Greece.
A1  - de Zegher F.
A1  - Ibanez L. 
Y1  - 2022//
N2  - Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is a prevalent disorder in adolescent girls and young women. PCOS is commonly driven by ectopic (hepato-visceral or central) fat accumulation and insulin resistance which, in turn, are secondary to fat excess in subcutaneous adipose tissue. The prime focus of PCOS treatment should thus be to reduce this central fat excess. This can often be achieved with lifestyle measures that combine regular exercise with a healthy diet, and with respect for biorhythm and sleep. If such lifestyle measures do not suffice, then the standard pharmacological addition is an oral contraceptive (OC), which is currently prescribed off-label for the vast majority of young patients with PCOS. OCs attenuate the clinical symptoms of androgen excess and they elicit regular pseudo-menses but do not revert the central fat excess so that, upon treatment discontinuation in adulthood, the entire PCOS phenotype (including oligo-anovulatory subfertility) tends to readily reappear. Pharmacological treatments under study include glucagon-like peptide-1 (GLP-1) agonists such as liraglutide or semaglutide for PCOS patients with obesity. Combinations of generics that act through different pathways, are among the alternatives under investigation; one example is SPIOMET, which is a low-dose combination of spironolacton (50 mg/d), pioglitazone (7.5 mg/d) and metformin (850 mg/d). The effects of SPIOMET vs those of an OC (containing ethinylestradiol-levonorgestrel) were investigated in two randomized, open-label, single-center pilot studies performed in non-obese girls with PCOS who did not need contraception. The pooled results disclosed that SPIOMET had more normalizing effects than OC on ectopic fat and insulin resistance, and resulted in a 3-fold higher post-treatment ovulation rate [1-3]. The combined effects of a lifestyle intervention plus SPIOMET's components (in a single tablet) will be further tested in a randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled, multi-center study within a project (SPIOMET4HEALTH) funded by the EU's Horizon 2020 Research and Innovation program.Copyright © 2022
