T1  - Audit of referral of subfertile couples from primary care and their management in the secondary care
T3  - RCOG National Trainees Conference, NTC 2021. Virtual.
A1  - Mukhtar S.
A1  - Rai M.
A1  - Hakim H. 
Y1  - 2021//
N2  - Introduction Subfertility is common in the UK. This audit had two parts. The first part to assess the compliance of referrals according to NICE Guideline and to emphasise the importance of early referral in older women and women with a known cause of fertility or history of predisposing factors. The second part was the re-audit of the overall management in secondary care and to understand the pitfalls in the system. Methods It was a retrospective audit with 100 number of patients. Data were collected electronically. Results 25% of patients with BMI >30 75% of women with a known cause of fertility or history of predisposing factors and age of 36 or more were referred after 18 months. 85% started to try before the age of 36. >70% with no documentation about lifestyle advise during secondary care management. PCOS is the most common ovulatory dysfunction and 70% treated with clomiphene only or a combination with metformin. Main indications for IVF referrals were a male factor and unexplained fertility. Re-audit found the 100% outcome to suggestions made last time, including sending proformas to patients before clinic and properly filled referral from primary care. Conclusion Time is crucial for the subfertile couple as increasing maternal age and long duration of subfertility have a negative impact on the success rate of IVF. More awareness needed for prompt referral and to improve overall fertility outcome. Proformas sent to the couple before coming to the clinic with all the baseline investigation results save time drastically and improve patients satisfaction.
