352. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 629635490
T1  - Insulin Resistance and Cardiovascular Disease
T2  - Contemporary Endocrinology
A1  - Haley J.E.
A1  - Urbina E.M. 
Y1  - 2020//
N2  - The worldwide prevalence of obesity doubled from 1980 to 2008. It is well recognized that hypertension, dyslipidemia, insulin resistance (IR), and obesity increase the risk for cardiovascular (CV) events in adults. There are numerous proposed mechanisms to explain the association between IR and early CV disease. These include actions at the level of the vascular endothelium, including alterations in the normal vasodilatory nitric oxide response, increased proinflammatory chemokines, and decreased levels of adiponectin (an anti-inflammatory adipocyte). Hyperglycemia, which is associated with insulin resistance, has also been implicated in endothelial dysfunction through several mechanisms that result in decreased nitric oxide bioavailability or nitric oxide production. Compensatory increases in insulin secretion have also been implicated in the development of hypertension through actions at the level of the kidney, as well as stimulation of the sympathetic nervous system. Despite the lack of hard cardiovascular events in children with insulin resistance, a growing body of evidence suggests that insulin resistance in youth results in target organ damage (TOD). In obese youth, insulin resistance is associated with increased left ventricular mass and abnormal vascular structure and function. In order to reduce cardiovascular disease (CVD) in adults, CV risk must be addressed in youth. The 2011 National Institutes of Health (NIH) guidelines on CV risk reduction in youth provide an evidence base for identifying and managing major CV risk factors (CVRF) from infancy to young adulthood. Many of the interventions focusing on CVRF reduction have been shown to improve insulin sensitivity and target organ damage. Lifestyle modifications that include improved diet and exercise patterns and/or weight loss and use of insulin-sensitizing medications are associated with reduction in insulin resistance. This improvement in metabolic control is, in turn, associated with reduction in levels of CV target organ damage. Diagnosis and treatment of IR in youth is imperative to prevent target organ damage that can lead to premature cardiovascular disease.Copyright © 2020, Springer Nature Switzerland AG.
