404. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 634080779
T1  - Quantifying medium- A nd long-term issues facing prostate cancer survivors. Two decades of results from the NSW Prostate Cancer Care and Outcomes Study (PCOS)
T3  - Mini Annual Scientific Meeting of the Australian and New Zealand Urogenital and Prostate Cancer Trials Group, ANZUP 2020. Virtual.
A1  - Mazariego C. 
Y1  - 2020//
N2  - In 2000 the NSW Prostate Cancer Care and Outcomes Study (PCOS) was established with the intention of describing the patterns and outcomes of care for men with prostate cancer (PC). Since inception PCOS results have made important contributions nationally and internationally to highlight quality of life and supportive care trajectories of PC survivors. The objective of this presentation is to review and highlight PCOS result, with the primary aim to describe the quality of life of men with up to 15 years after diagnosis. Method(s): PCOS is a population wide cohort study including 2000 cases and 500 controls recruited through the NSW Cancer Registry. Cases were men aged less than 70, diagnosed with pathologically confirmed prostate cancer. Controls were age and postcode matched to cases and selected at random from the electoral roll. Patient reported outcomes were assessed at baseline then at 1,2,3,5,10 and 15 years after recruitment. Multiple sub-studies investigating supportive care needs, patient preferences, use of complimentary medicines, effects of circulating Vitamin D and supportive care needs of partners were embedded in this cohort. Result(s): Fifteen years after initial treatment for localised disease all primary treatment groups reported high levels of sexual dysfunction ranging from 62.3% (no initial active treatment) to 83.0% (non-nerve sparing radical prostatectomy) compared with controls (42.7%). 37% of men reported that they had unmet supportive care needs 15 years after diagnosis. 51% used a wide variety of complementary or lifestyle medicines up to 10 years after diagnosis. Circulating Vitamin D (1,25(OH)2D) levels were inversely associated with all-cause mortality (HR for highest relative to lowest quartile = 0.28;95% CI.0.15-0.52) and PC-specific mortality (HR = 0.26;95% CI: 0.07-1.00) in men with aggressive PC. Conclusion(s): The survivorship experience after localised PC can vary hugely between men. While many survive well and long after their original diagnosis almost all report changed quality of life. A notable proportion reported unmet supportive care needs particularly for greater help with sexual problems both shortly after and many years from diagnosis.
