405. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2009003169
T1  - P.282 Hippocampal volume changes are linked to depressive symptoms independent of sex-steroid hormone manipulation: a pharmacological structural MRI study
T3  - 9th Annual Meeting of the International College of OC Spectrum Disorders held in conjunction with ECNP OCRN. Virtual, Online.
A1  - Larsen C.B.
A1  - Ganz M.
A1  - Henningsson S.
A1  - Pinborg A.
A1  - Frokjaer V. 
Y1  - 2020//
N2  - Background: In some women, hormonal fluctuations may trigger depressive episodes, but the exact risk mechanisms remain elusive. We here report from a pharmacological sex-hormone manipulation model conceptualised to study such risk mechanisms. Using this model, we previously showed that a subgroup of women develop depressive symptoms in response to manipulation with a gonadotrophin-releasing hormone agonist (GnRHa) [1]. Intriguingly, the severity of symptoms correlated with the GnRHa-induced decrease in oestradiol concentrations, compromised serotonergic signalling [1], changes in cognitive processing networks known to be key in depression [2,3], and altered hippocampal brain connectivity at rest [4]. The aim here was to evaluate if the depressogenic effect of GnRHa-intervention also was linked to changes in hippocampal volume. We hypothesised that hippocampal volume would decrease in response to intervention and that this phenomenon would be positively associated with the emergence of depressive symptoms in the GnRHa-group and with the magnitude of the GnRHa-induced decrease in oestradiol. Method(s): In a double-blind, placebo-controlled intervention study [1], 63 healthy premenopausal women (mean age 24.3+/-4.9 years) were randomized to receive either placebo or GnRHa (3.6 mg goserelin implant) on menstrual cycle day 22. Of these, 60 women (placebo n=30, GnRHa n=30) completed follow-up 16.2+/-2.6 days after intervention (dropouts due to anovulation, pregnancy and scanner failure). Outcomes at baseline (menstrual cycle day 6.6+/-2.2) and follow-up included 17-item Hamilton Depression Rating Scale scores (HDRS), log transformed oestradiol concentrations and hippocampal volume assessed with magnetic resonance imaging (MRI). T1-weighted structural MRI images were segmented in Freesurfer and hippocampal volumes were extracted for statistical analysis in R. We used a mean of left and right hippocampal volume for all analyses. Change in mean hippocampal volume (DELTAhippocampus), HDRS scores (DELTAHDRS) and oestradiol (DELTAoestradiol) were modelled as follow-up minus baseline. We used linear regression to determine the main effect of intervention on DELTAhippocampus, group-by-DELTAhippocampus interaction effect and main effect of DELTAhippocampus on DELTAHDRS, and, in the GnRHa-group, to determine the main effect of DELTAoestradiol on DELTAhippocampus and the DELTAoestradiol-by-DELTAhippocampus interaction effect on DELTAHDRS. Result(s): The effect of GnRHa-intervention, including DELTAoestradiol, on DELTAHDRS was published previously [1]. We found no main effect of group on DELTAhippocampus (p=0.99) or evidence for a group-by-DELTAhippocampus interaction effect on DELTAHDRS (p=0.65). However, there was a main effect of DELTAhippocampus on DELTAHDRS, independent of group (beta=-0.016, s.e.=0.005, p=0.021). Within the GnRHa-group, we observed no main effect of DELTAoestradiol on DELTAhippocampus (p=0.81), nor a DELTAoestradiol-by-DELTAhippocampus interaction effect on DELTAHDRS (beta=0.029, s.e.=0.018, p=0.12). Conclusion(s): Our data do not support that sex-hormone manipulation with GnRHa changes hippocampal volume per se. However, fluctuations, either natural or related to pharmacological manipulations, in hippocampal volume appear to increase the susceptibility to develop mild depressive symptoms, even over a period of two weeks. Further, hippocampal volume reductions and the magnitude of oestradiol decreases in the GnRHa-group interacted on a trend level in their association with emergence of depressive symptoms and our study design was most likely insufficiently powered to evaluate this question. Thus, we cannot exclude that these mechanisms work synergistically in promoting vulnerability to depression in some women. Disclosure statement: This abstract is financially supported by The Independent Research Fund Denmark, The Lundbeck Foundation, The Capital Region of Denmark, Foundation for Health Research and Research Fund of the Mental Health Services, Capital Region of Denmark.Copyright © 2020
