408. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2008361596
T1  - A RARE NEUROLOGICAL DISORDER MIMICKING RECURRENT ANGIOEDEMA
T3  - 2020 Annual Scientific Meeting of the American College of Allergy, Asthma and Immunology. Virtual, Online.
A1  - Patel A.
A1  - Lei D.
A1  - Grammer L. 
Y1  - 2020//
N2  - Introduction: Awareness of angioedema mimickers prevents misdiagnosis and delay in appropriate treatment. We present a case of recurrent lip swelling due to Melkersson-Rosenthal Syndrome. Case Description: A 36 y/o female with PCOS presented with 3 months of recurrent asymmetrical right upper lip swelling with fluctuating episode severity and no other systemic symptoms. Trial of valacyclovir (for potential herpetic lesion), diphenhydramine and methylprednisolone were all unsuccessful in improving symptoms. Antihistamine regimen of levocetirizine 5 mg daily, fexofenadine 180 mg daily and famotidine 20 mg twice daily led to slight reduction in symptom frequency, but episodes continued to occur weekly. C1 esterase inhibitor level was normal. No changes in lifestyle or medications were identified and family history was unremarkable. Given persistence of swelling and lack of response to oral steroids, patient was referred to Dermatology for biopsy. She was noted to have mild facial palsy at that time. Right upper lip biopsy demonstrated granulomatous dermatitis consistent with Melkersson-Rosenthal Syndrome. She is currently receiving treatment with intra-lesional triamcinolone acetonide injections every 3 to 6 months. Discussion(s): Melkersson-Rosenthal Syndrome should be considered as part of the differential for lip swelling. This is a rare neurological disorder presenting with recurrent, long-lasting facial swelling involving one or both lips and usually begins in young adulthood with females more often affected than males. Some individuals also display facial palsy and/or fissured tongue. This case highlights that it is vital for Allergy/Immunology specialists to thoroughly understand the many mimics of angioedema-a condition they commonly diagnose and treat.Copyright © 2020
