470. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2001763420
T1  - Acupuncture for weight loss in Polycystic Ovary Syndrome: a qualitative study exploring feasibility and acceptability
T3  - International Congress on Complementary Medicine Research: Pathways and Partnerships. Brisbane Australia.
A1  - Ee C.
A1  - Smith C.
A1  - Costello M.
A1  - MacMillan F.
A1  - Moran L.
A1  - Baylock B.
A1  - Teede H. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Background: Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS) is a common female reproductive disorder with multiple manifestations. We aimed to engage patients in co-design and assess feasibility and acceptability of methods for a randomised controlled trial (RCT) on acupuncture and telephone-based health coaching for weight management in overweight/obese women with PCOS. Method(s): We recruited women who had PCOS, aged 18-45 years, with a body mass index >25 kg/m2, using social media. Two face-to-face focus group meetings and three semi-structured telephone interviews were conducted (n = 10). We analysed data using thematic analysis and aimed to compare and contrast motivations for joining the trial between women who were actively trying to conceive (n = 7) and not trying to conceive (n = 3). Attitudes to, knowledge and experiences of acupuncture; perceptions and attitudes towards the interventions in the RCT, the outcomes of importance; and barriers and facilitators to successful trial recruitment and retention were explored. Result(s): Attitudes towards acupuncture were positive, and trial design was acceptable with appointment flexibility requested. Ideal enrolment time, if women were trying to conceive, was six months prior to conception. Women supported three-month intervention and use of sham acupuncture as a control. Women spoke of altruistic intentions in enrolling, and those trying to conceive voiced a need for support from their family, health coaches, and peers. Telephone-based health coaching offered welcome support and accountability. Conclusion(s): Acupuncture is a likely acceptable adjunct to lifestyle interventions for weight loss in PCOS, and a sham-controlled trial is feasible and acceptable to women with PCOS.Copyright © 2019
