515. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 625506904
T1  - Audit of the recurrent pregnancy loss clinic at the Women's Hospital Birmingham
T3  - RCOG National Trainees Conference , NTC 2018. Birmingham United Kingdom.
A1  - Parry G. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - Introduction Recurrent pregnancy loss (RPL) is defined as the loss of two or more pregnancies. RPL affects up to 5% of couples and can lead to psychological distress. The cause of RPL is unknown in nearly 50% of cases. RPL clinics are used to identify the aetiology. Methods We performed a retrospective audit of patients referred to the RPL clinic. Data were gathered from patients' case notes using a data collection form. The data form was modelled on the current Green-top Guideline No. 17 and the prospective ESHRE guidelines. Results 50 patients were included in the audit. 70% of patients had experienced 3 and above consecutive miscarriages before referral. A significant number of women were not counselled regarding lifestyle factors. BMI was not recorded in any male partners and 16% of partners received lifestyle advice. 6% of patients were diagnosed with antiphospholipid syndrome and all were advised to start clexane and aspirin once pregnant. 44% of patients had a congenital uterine abnormality diagnosed/confirmed, most commonly PCOS (41%). 43% of patients received or were offered progesterone once pregnant. 12% of discharges were the result of a successful pregnancy. In 37% of patients a cause for RPL was identified, all of which had maternal origin. Conclusion Lifestyle advice is not offered to all couples. Despite rigorous testing most patients do not find the cause of their RPL and are offered empirical progesterone therapy or reassurance. The number of women who have a successful pregnancy is low; however, this could be under-reported.
