516. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 624607343
T1  - The effects of obesity on female fertility
T3  - 22nd FIGO World Congress of Gynecology and Obstetrics. Rio de Janeiro Brazil.
A1  - Vilarino F.L.
A1  - Rodrigues R.M.P.
A1  - DeSantana E Sarti F.C. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - Objectives: Obesity is associated with neuroendocrine reproductive alterations and decreased fertility. The objective of our study is to present the harmful effects of this comorbidity on female fertility based on the most updated literature. Method(s): The PubMed/Medline database was searched for the best available scientific evidence using the descriptor "effects of obesity on female fertility". We found 23 articles, published between the years 2008 and 2018, of which 10 were selected. The exclusion criteria were review studies, meta-analyzes, case report and non-compatible theme. Result(s): Studies indicate the benefit of improved ovulation when preceded by lifestyle modification that offered a significantly better cumulative ovulation rate in obese patients with polycystic ovary syndrome (Lifestyle: 62.0%, p=0.03), also, another study showed that ovulation rates were higher after weight loss:oral contraceptives 46%; Lifestyle, 60%; and Combined, 67% (p<0.05). In addition, a decrease in insulin sensitivity may constitute a mechanical link between obesity and changes in LH secretion with the frequency of spontaneous and insulin-stimulated pulsatile LH secretion was increased by 17.9%+/-9.0% and 26.5%+/-9.0% (p<.05) Conclusion(s): Thus, we conclude that obesity is harmful to female fertility, being associated with neuroendocrine and metabolic disorders that lead to ovarian dysfunction and, consequently, fertility rates. It has been shown that the lifestyle change, such as weight loss, presented a beneficial pattern for the treatment of fertilization, also associated with drug treatment.
