526. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 623114195
T1  - Obesity and cardio metabolic risk factors in the adolescent transgender population
T3  - 100th Annual Meeting of the Endocrine Society, ENDO 2018. Chicago, IL United States.
A1  - Ramakrishna A.
A1  - Kumar S.
A1  - Chang A.Y.
A1  - Nippoldt T.B.
A1  - Davidge-Pitts C.J.
A1  - Spee R.
A1  - Nicole I.
A1  - Gonzales C.
A1  - Lteif A.N. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - Background: Pediatric obesity has assumed epidemic proportions, with up to 17% of children in the United States being obese. Transgender college students have been reported to have higher rates of obesity and underweight compared to nontransgender students and were less likely to meet recommendations for physical activity. The complex psychosocial milieu surrounding transgender youth might put them at a higher risk for obesity. The objective of this study was to determine the prevalence of obesity and cardio metabolic risk factors amongst transgender children and adolescents prior to initiation of cross-sex hormone therapy. Method/Results: Medical records of 57 patients (age 7 - 18 yrs) with a transgender related diagnosis, and who were evaluated at the Mayo Clinic Transgender and Intersex Specialty Care Clinic (TISCC) between 2015 and 2017, were reviewed. Two patients were excluded due to initiation of cross-sex hormone therapy prior to presentation. The values are reported as median (IQR1-IQR3). 42 patients were assigned female at birth and 13 were assigned male at birth. The median age at presentation was 15 years (13-16). Abnormal lipids and blood pressure were defined as per most recent NHLBI guidelines. The median BMI percentile of those assigned female at birth was 90.5 (58-96), with 59.5% having a BMI >= 85th percentile. 21.4% were overweight, 26.2 % were obese and 11.9% were severely obese (BMI >= 99th BMI z score >=2.33. The median BMI percentile of those assigned male at birth was 93 (67- 97) and 69.2% patients had a BMI >= 85th percentile. 23.1% of these patients were overweight, 30.8 % were obese and 15.3% were severely obese (BMI >=99th percentile). The median BMI Z-score was 1.5 (0.51-2.11) and 15.3% of the patients had a BMI z score >= 2.33. Amongst the patients evaluated, 10.9% and 3.6 % had prehypertension and hypertension respectively based on systolic BP while 9.1% and 5.4% had prehypertension and hypertension respectively based on diastolic BP. 23 patients had laboratory testing prior to initiation of cross-sex hormone therapy. Total cholesterol was borderline high in 39.1% and high in 21.7%. HDL cholesterol was abnormal in 2/3rd of the patients (borderline low in 30.4% and low in 34.7%). LDL cholesterol was borderline high in 8.6% and high in 0% patients. Triglycerides were borderline high in 26.1% and high in 4.3%. 15% patients had abnormal liver function studies. The median HbA1c was 5.4 (4.8-7.8). Two patients had a diagnosis of PCOS and one patient had a diagnosis of Type 2 Diabetes mellitus. Conclusion(s): The prevalence of obesity and adverse cardiometabolic factors is extremely high in transgender children and adolescents. Lifestyle interventions should be incorporated in the routine care of these individuals especially given the potential risk of worsening of metabolic parameters on cross-sex hormone therapy.
