531. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 621268650
T1  - Is there any correlation between endocrine profiles and metabolic disorders in women with polycystic ovarian syndrome?
T3  - 65th Annual Scientific Meeting of the Society for Gynecologic Investigation, SGI 2018. San Diego, CA United States.
A1  - Pilgrim J.
A1  - Tam L.M.
A1  - Hung L.V.
A1  - Phuong Le N.T.
A1  - Duong L.D.
A1  - Nguyen Sa L.V.
A1  - Kong P.C.
A1  - Thanh C.N.
A1  - DeCherney A.H.
A1  - Hill M.J. 
Y1  - 2018//
N2  - INTRODUCTION: Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is a common endocrine and metabolic disorder that affects 6-18% of women. In addition to the hormonal disorders that cause infertility, PCOS is related to metabolic disorders including obesity, glucose intolerance, dyslipidemia, hypertension, type 2 DM and cardiovascular disease. Data on metabolic disorders in PCOS is still limited and lack of uniformity in terms of race, geographic location, human-origin, age, sample size or lifestyle. METHOD(S): Cross-sectional description of 759 cases of reproductive-age women diagnosed with PCOS by Rotterdam criteria (391) and non-PCOS (368) at 3 ART centers in central Vietnam receiving care from June 2016 to June 2017. Control group consisted of infertile women without PCOS, having regular menstrual cycles, no ovarian disease (ovary cyst/tumor or endometriosis), without history of ovarian surgery or determined ovarian failure. Clinical characteristics, basic hormonal profile, AMH, lipidemia variables, fasting blood glucose and glucose tolerance testing were performed. Data was analyzed using SPSS 19.0. RESULT(S): Mean age of the PCOS group was 29.21 +/- 4.20. Prevalence of PCOS in patients >35 years of age was 26.4% versus 58.2% in patients <35 (RR=0.45 with 95%CI: 0.35-0.59). The prevalence of PCOS in primary infertility was 1.3 times higher than that in secondary infertility group. The PCOS group had a 1.2-fold increase in overweight BMI. The mean waist circumference and waist/hip ratio was higher than that of control group. Mean AMH of the PCOS group (8.94+/-5.68 ng/ml) was significantly higher than the controls (3.49+/-2.12 ng/ml), while the LH/ FSH ratio >2 increased by 2.4 fold (RR=2.4 with 95%CI: 2.13-2.62) and testosterone levels increased by 1.75 fold (RR=1.75 with 95% CI: 1.56-1.97). Lipidemia dysfunction was observed in 176 cases of PCOS (45%), total cholesterol 21.0%, triglycerides 21.5%, LDL-C 25.6% and low HDL 7.9%. Glycemia disturbances occurred in 119 cases (30.4%) with abnormal glucose tolerance test after 2 hours (25.0%). In the PCOS group, overweight women were at increased risk of metabolic disorders 1.46 fold (RR = 1.46 with 95%CI: 1.26-1.70). In addition, the risk of metabolic dysfunction when considering the AMH> 4.42 (RR=0.92; 95% CI: 0.76-1.12), LH/FSH ratio >= 2 (RR=1.05, 95% CI 0.89-1.24), Testosterone> 0.53 (RR=0.85, KTC95% 0.65-1.12) found no significant difference. CONCLUSION(S): Metabolic disorders are common amongst infertile patients with PCOS in Central Vietnam. Appropriate screening strategy, early detection and timely intervention are needed to prevent systemic complications related to metabolic disorders.
