607. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 70138899
T1  - Clinical effectiveness research: Lessons from STEP-BD
T3  - 4th Biennial Conference of the International Society for Bipolar Disorders. Sao Paulo Brazil.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Sachs G. 
Y1  - 2010//
N2  - Bipolar Disorder is a common complex condition associated with high rates of disability and high health care costs. The Systematic Treatment Enhancement Program for Bipolar Disorder (STEPBD) was conceived in response to an NIMH request for proposals to study the effectiveness of treatments for Bipolar Disorder. Designed for implementation in routine practice across a variety of settings, STEP-BD offered research platform based on a disease management program in which standardized assessments were linked to critical decision points in clinical management pathways. A key aspect of the STEP-BD approach to effectiveness research was the development of novel outcome variables such as durable recovery and days well, which were intended to capture more meaningful results compared to change in formal rating scale scores. In recognition of the strengths and weaknesses inherent in any single trial design, STEP-BD used a common assessment package to gather data on subjects in "randomized care pathways and the preference driven "standard care pathways". While results of each are limited by accession bias, the STEP-BD results that can be generalized with the greatest confidence are those where the analysis of data from open and randomized samples produced similar results. This presentation describes major findings and strategies used in STEP-BD to improve the treatment of Bipolar disorder: a simple conceptual model which integrates assessments and management, and several specialized elements used in the STEP-BD assessment package. Standard antidepressant medications are the most commonly used treatment for bipolar depression, however, results from STEP-BD found no more acute antidepressant benefit when these agents were added to mood stabilizers then when placebo added. Conversely, three forms of intensive psychosocial intervention (Cognitive Behavior Therapy, Family Focused Therapy, and Interpersonal Social Rhythm Therapy) were found to be significantly better than the control condition for bipolar depression. STEP-BD also found a significant association between valproate use and the risk of polycystic ovarian syndrome and contributed a large number of samples with high confidence diagnosis to the NIH genetics repository.
