609. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 70141293
T1  - Impaired glucose tolerance in adolescents with polycystic ovarian syndrome
T3  - 24th Annual Clinical Meeting of the North American Society for Pediatric and Adolescent Gynecology, NASPAG. Las Vegas, NV United States.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Rackow B.W.
A1  - Thomas M.
A1  - Duran E.J.
A1  - Flannery C.A.
A1  - Burgert T.S. 
Y1  - 2010//
N2  - Background: Polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS), the most common endocrinopathy of reproductive-age women, is increasingly appreciated in adolescents. Adult women with PCOS have a high prevalence (30-40%) of impaired glucose tolerance and type 2 diabetes; the prevalence of metabolic abnormalities in adolescents with PCOS has not been well established. Method(s): Sixty-five adolescents from our multi-specialty adolescent PCOS program (MAPP) were enrolled into an ongoing IRB approved cohort study. All subjects had a complete history and examination, transabdominal pelvic ultrasound and hormone laboratory testing. Standard (75 g glucose) 2 hour oral glucose tolerance test (OGTT) was performed indiscriminately in all girls referred to the MAPP. In accordance with American Diabetes Association guidelines, impaired fasting glucose was defined as fasting plasma glucose >=100mg/dl and impaired glucose tolerance (IGT) as 2 hour post-challenge plasma glucose >=140mg/dl. The homeostatic model assessment of insulin resistance (HOMA-IR) was calculated with fasting glucose and insulin values. Statistical analysis was performed using chi-square, ANOVA and t-test as appropriate. Data are presented as mean+/- standard deviation and percent. Result(s): All subjects met the Androgen Excess Society (2006) criteria for polycystic ovarian syndrome: ovarian dysfunction based on oligo-ovulation or polycystic ovarian morphology on ultrasound, and hyperandrogenism as evidenced by hirsutism or hyper-androgenemia; other etiologies of symptoms were also excluded. Mean subject age was 15.6 +/- 1.6 years, and mean body mass index (BMI) was 31.6 +/- 7.7 kg/m2. Twelve of 65 adolescents with PCOS demonstrated IGT (18%). When IGT was assessed based on BMI categories, there were no differences in the prevalence of IGT between lean, overweight and obese groups (p=0.82): 14% of lean adolescents (BMI <25kg/ m2) had IGT as did 14% of those with class 2 obesity (BMI>35kg/m2), and 22% of the overweight (BMI 25-29kg/m2) and 25% of the class 1 obesity (BMI 30-35 kg/m2) groups had IGT. Only one subject demonstrated impaired fasting glucose (1.8%). While HO-MA was slightly higher in the obese adolescents, there was no significant difference in HOMA among the different BMI categories (p = 0.5): 2.9 +/- 1.5 in the lean adolescents, 3.9 +/- 3.7 in the overweight group, and 4.2 +/- 3.9 for the combined obese groups. Conclusion(s): Adolescents with PCOS are at increased risk for IGT and insulin resistance. In contrast to our expectations, IGT was not only identified in obese adolescents, but also in lean adolescents and those with modest BMI increase. Insulin resistance as assessed by HOMA, albeit lower in the leaner subjects, was present in all categories without significant differences. Limiting assessment of glucose and insulin levels to the fasting state can miss the diagnosis of IGT independent of the degree of obesity. Therefore, all adolescents who meet criteria for the diagnosis of PCOS warrant evaluation with an OGTT. Early intervention with lifestyle changes and insulin-sensitizing agents, when indicated, may improve long-term outcomes for these adolescents.
