610. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 70091676
T1  - The metabolic syndrome: What really should be done
T3  - 19th European Childhood Obesity Group Meeting 'Moving Towards Health'. Dublin Ireland.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Malecka-Tendera E. 
Y1  - 2010//
N2  - As there is an increasing incidence of overweight and obesity in children, there is also a simultaneous increase in frequency of the metabolic disturbances that were previously uncommon in pediatrics. Childhood obesity may be complicated by impaired fasting glucose (IFG) and impaired glucose tolerance (IGT), which are both strong predictors of diabetes mellitus type 2 (DMT2). They are usually heralded or accompanied by hyperinsulinemia and insulin resistance (1,2). Dyslipidemia, particularly high levels of triglycerides and low HDL-cholesterol, together with elevated blood pressure, are known as risk factors for premature atherosclerosis. Some children may have hepatic manifestation of metabolic abnormalities known as nonalcoholic fatty liver disease (3). Metabolic syndrome (MS) is a constellation of metabolic and anthropometric parameters that is known to increase the risk of cardiovascular disease (CVD) and DMT2 in adults. The MS may be diagnosed in 1-10% of normal weight and in 10-67% of obese children and adolescents (4-7). The difference depends mostly on the applied criteria, however race, age, degree, type and duration of obesity may also be an important factor. In 2007, the International Diabetes Federation (IDF) proposed a new set of criteria to define MS in children and adolescents, with waist circumference being the core feature, as children with intraabdominal fat accumulation are at particular risk for MS development (8,9). To compensate for variations in child development and ethnic origin percentiles were used instead of the fixed cut-off points (Table I). It should be emphasized that many obese children in whom the criteria for MS diagnosis are not fulfilled, may still have important metabolic abnormalities (10,11). It is not known whether the individual components of MS increase cardiovascular risk differently from the full-blown syndrome. The lack of diagnosis of MS may cause the delay of treatment, while particular components of MS, for example visceral obesity, are independent risk factors of cardiovascular disorders as well as increased mortality. The attempts to establish or exclude the MS diagnosis in obese child are therefore not fully justified.The relationship between MS and the risk of CVD have been well documented in adults but there are few studies showing that the presence of the syndrome in children is putting them at increased risk of adult cardiovascular disease. Morrison et al (12) in a 25-year follow-up evaluation of students from Princeton, found the incidence of table presented CVD to be 19.4% in young adults with MS diagnosed in childhood, compared to only 1.5% in subjects without MS in pediatric age. However, the change in BMI was also highly associated with the development of MS, as for every increase in age specific BMI percentile of 10 points, the risk of MS in adulthood increased by 24%. With respect to the latter finding some authors challenge the view that the presence of obesity in a child is an independent risk factor for CVD and believe that the association is simply the result of tracking of obesity from childhood to adulthood. The cornerstone of the therapy of metabolic disorders in MS is the treatment of obesity, and especially its prevention. According to Dietary Guidelines of American Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) a healthy diet should be recommended to all children older than two years (13). For those who have a family history of obesity, dyslipidemia or CVD, AAP recommends reduced-fat milk as early as between 12-24 months of age. A fasting lipid profile should be performed in these children after two years of age and no later than at 10 years. Nutritional and physical activity counseling is a recommended approach. In pediatric patients with an unknown family history or who are overweight or obese, a fasting lipid profile is recommended. In obese children with a high triglyceride and low HDL-cholesterol concentration, treatment is focused ondecreasing the BMI percentile. It has been demonstrated that the components of MS can be improved even by relatively small decreases in body mass (14). For some overweight children maintenance of weight, while growth progresses, may be also beneficial. In several obese children, high total cholesterol and/or LDLcholesterol concentration may be present. Some of these children may have a strong family history for CVD and should be tested for familial hypercholesterolemia. These children require a higher level of intervention. Implementation of a more strict diet is better achieved with the help of an experienced dietitian. However, if diet change does not lower LDL-cholesterol to acceptable levels, pharmacological intervention should be considered. Lipid modifying drug therapy in children with familial forms of hypercholesterolemia is rarely needed before the age of 10 years (15). In older children, statin therapy is usually prescribed. Before therapy initiation, baseline liver and muscle enzymes (transaminases and creatine kinase) should be measured. The initial goal is to lower LDL-cholesterol concentration below 160 mg/dl, but the target of 130mg/dl should be put in perspective, especially if other components of MS are present. Routine monitoring of growth and pubertal development is important in every patient. There is less information about the treatment of hypertriglyceridemia and low HDL-cholesterol level in children but fibrates seem to be effective when diet itself does not improve the lipid profile. They should be used with caution because they may cause similar adverse effects as statins (13). According to AAP (16) obese children with two or more other risk factors for DMT2 (family history, high risk ethnicity, polycystic ovaries, acanthosis nigricans) should have fasting plasma glucose tested at least every two years. If IGT is diagnosed, they should receive behavior intervention and be monitored closely. Diagnosis of DMT2 needs appropriate treatment with Metformin or insulin. There are some anecdotal reports demonstrating the beneficial role of Metformin in treating severely obese children with MS. In a randomized, double-blind, placebo controlled trial Yanovskiet al (17) reported significant weight loss, improvement in serum glucose levels and insulin resistance as well as reduction in total cholesterol levels in a group of 6-12 years old children treated with Metformin for 6 months. However, the authors admitted that the results were not sufficient to recommend this treatment in clinical practice. In conclusion - the concept that MS in children is predictive for CVD in later period of life remains to be prospectively evaluated. Individuals with diagnosed risk factors, which are often multifactorial, require therapeutic lifestyle changes or clinical treatment regardless of fulfilling the criteria of MS.
