611. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 70300041
T1  - Long-term follow-up of PCOSpatients with oligomenorrhea and infertility: The LIPCOS Trial
T3  - 20th World Congress on Fertility and Sterility, IFFS 2010. Munich Germany.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Ohnolz F.
A1  - Stassek J.
A1  - Berg F.D.
A1  - Kiechle M.
A1  - Seifert-Klauss V. 
Y1  - 2010//
N2  - Introduction While studies on the influence of serum testosterone and cycle length on reproductive outcome have advanced the understanding of PCOS, little is known on the influence of pregnancy or parenthood on the course of PCOS. In this study we characterize the long term changes of PCOS related symptoms in regard to the occurrence of pregnancy and lifestyle interventions. Methods and Patients The LIPCOS study invited women diagnosed with oligomenorrhea and infertility or PCOS in 1991 to 2009 to a systematic follow-up visit. Intra-individual change of cycle length, clinical signs of hyperandrogenemia, as well as serum testosterone, BMI and lifestyle changes were compared and correlated with the occurrence of pregnancy in the preceding 10 years. The follow-up consisted of a detailed hormonal profile, ultrasound evaluation of the ovaries and measurement of insulin secretion after a standardized test meal. Results Over the preceding 10 years, average cycle length shortened from 55.1 to 50 days (n = 49, 35.4 years). BMI increased from 22.8 to 24.8. Total testosterone (TT) levels decreased from 0.75 ng/ml to 0.5 ng/ml (n = 48). While 42.9% (n = 9) of mothers (n = 21, mean 38.52 years, BMI 24.7) reported a shortening of cycle length (55.1 to 49.6 days), only 35.7% (n = 10) of childless women (n = 28, mean 33.1 years, BMI 24.9) reported this (55.2 to 50.2 days). Present TT levels were lower in mothers than in childless patients (0.45 vs 0.53 ng/dl). Regarding lifestyle interventions, mothers reported a healthier nutrition and a more regular everyday life compared to childless patients (85.7 vs 78.6%; 90.5 vs 68%). The standardized test meal revealed no impaired glucose tolerance or diabetes, but insulin secretion 60 min after glucose exposure was higher in childless women than in mothers (22.83 vs 18.05 uU/ ml). Clinical hyperandrogenemia remained unchanged over the years. Conclusion While age has already been shown to be associated with cycle length, the association of long-term intra-individual change of cycle length, insulin resistance, clinical hyperandrogenemia, and serum testosterone with the occurence of pregnancy is new to be presented.
