613. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 70289448
T1  - Long-term follow-up of PCOS-patients with oligomenorrhea and infertility: The LIPCOS trial
T3  - 58th Congress of the German Society for Gynecology and Obstetrics (Deutsche Gesellschaft fur Gynakologie und Geburtshilfe, DGGG). Munich Germany.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Ohnolz F.
A1  - Stassek J.
A1  - Hanusch Y.
A1  - Berg D.
A1  - Kiechle M.
A1  - Seifert-Klauss V. 
Y1  - 2010//
N2  - Objective: Long-term changes of PCOS-related symptoms were studied with regard to the occurrence of pregnancy and lifestyle changes. Material(s) and Method(s): 378 women diagnosed with oligomenorrhea in 1991 to 2009 were invited to a follow-up visit. The LIPCOS (Lifestyle Interventions in PCOS) Trial compared and correlatedintra-individual change of cycle length, hyperandrogenemia, BMI and lifestyle changes with the occurrence of pregnancy. The follow-up consisted of a detailed hormonal profile, ultrasound classification of the ovaries (according to F. Geisthovel et al. [1]) and measurement of insulin secretion after standardized test meal. Result(s): Over the preceding 10 years, cycle length shortened from 55.1 to 50 days (n = 49, 35.4 years). Total testosterone (TT) decreased from 0.75 ng/ml (n = 14) to 0.5 ng/ml (n = 48). 42.9% (n = 9) of mothers (n = 21, mean 38.52 years, BMI 24.7) reported a shortening of cycle length (55.1-49.6 days), but only 35.7% (n = 10) of childless women (n = 28, mean 33.1 years, BMI 24.9; 55.2-50.2 days). Present TT levels were lower (0.45 vs. 0.53 ng/dl) and acne and alopecia were milder (14.3 and 28.6 vs. 46.4 and 57.1%) in mothers than in childless patients. Ovarian score was lower in mothers (0.8 vs. 0.96). Mothers reported a healthier nutrition and a more regular everyday life compared to childless patients (85.7 vs. 78.6%; 90.5 vs. 68%). The standardized test meal revealed no impaired glucose tolerance or diabetes, but insulin secretion 60 min. after glucose exposure was higher in childless women than in mothers (22.83 vs. 18.05 lU/ml). Conclusion(s): Long-term intra-individual change of cycle length and features of PCOS relate to motherhood.
