618. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 70197054
T1  - Results of a lifestyle programme for obese infertile women performed by a nurse practitioner
T3  - 25th Annual Meeting of the European Society of Human Reproduction and Embryology, ESHRE. Amsterdam Netherlands.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Bolster A.
A1  - Kuchenbecker W.
A1  - Groen H.
A1  - Land J.
A1  - Hoek A. 
Y1  - 2009//
N2  - Introduction: In western countries 35% of infertile women are overweight (BMI: 25-30 kg/m2) or obese (BMI >30 kg/m2). Overweight in women has deleterious effects on reproductive performance. Structured lifestyle programmes in various patient groups have shown to be most successful in achieving weight loss. Small cohort studies in obese infertile women show that weight loss of 5-10% improves reproductive outcome. In our clinic a lifestyle programme was embedded in infertility treatment. We investigated whether obese infertile women loose weight in a structured lifestyle programme. Furthermore, we assessed the spontaneous pregnancy chances in the study cohort. Material(s) and Method(s): The study was carried out between 2005-2008 in a tertiary referral center. All obese ovulatory and anovulatory infertile women who had a partner with total motile spermcount of >=10.106 and who had at least one patent tube were asked to participate in a lifestyle programme, performed by a nurse practitioner. The lifestyle advice consisted of low calorie diet (1200-1600 kcal per day) and increased physical activity (10.000 steps per day and 30 minutes of aerobics 3xper week), motivational counselling was offered. In 13 structured sessions (during 6 months) a personal programme with realistic goals and clear actions tailored on patient's wishes and possibilities, was implemented. In the participating cohort weight loss, the number of spontaneous pregnancies and the drop out rate were assessed in a 6 months period. Result(s): 60 women were included in the study (43 anovulatory and 17 ovulatory). At intake the mean age was 29+/-4.3 years, duration of infertility was 2.6+/-0.1 years and BMI 37.7+/-6.1 kg/m2. 34 patients completed the programme (57%), 4 are still in the programme (6%) and 22 dropped out (37%). Overall mean total weight loss was 4.2+/-5.8 kg; mean weight loss in patients completing the programme was 6.1+/-6.4 kg and in drop outs 1.3+/-2.9 kg (Mann-Whitney test: p <=0.002). Of the 34 patients who completed the programme 19 became pregnant spontaneously (56%). There were 15 pregnancies in anovulatory patients (35%) and 4 pregnancies in ovulatory patients (24%). Of the 22 patients who dropped out 3 conceived spontaneously (14%). Significantly more spontaneous pregnancies were obtained in patients completing the programme as compared to patients who dropped out (p <=0.002). Conclusion(s): This small cohort study in obese infertile women shows that women who complete a structured lifestyle programme loose significantly more weight as compared to women who drop out. Significantly more spontaneous pregnancies were obtained in the women who complied to the programme. Anovulatory patients benefit of weight loss, because they become ovulatory. Ovulatory patients also seem to benefit with respect to pregnancy chances, although the mechanism is unclear. Drop out of patients was high, mainly due to psychosocial aspects. These promising findings have to be confirmed in a larger cohort. We will perform a randomized clinical trial in obese infertile women, in which the costs and effects of a six months structured lifestyle programme, will be compared to "usual care".
