651. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 46020328
ID  - 17185790 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17185790]
T1  - Lifestyle choices, diet, and insulin sensitizers in polycystic ovary syndrome
A1  - Norman R.J.
A1  - Homan G.
A1  - Moran L.
A1  - Noakes M. 
Y1  - 2006//
N2  - Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is significantly affected by environmental regulators impacting on genetic predisposition. Lifestyle changes can significantly modulate the phenotype of this disease. Diet, exercise, smoking, stress, and other factors adversely affect reproductive outcomes in PCOS. These influences can be modulated by structure change in an individual or group. Lifestyle choices should be discussed in this group of patients. The role of insulin sensitizers, including metformin, has still to be determined in this condition. © 2006 by Humana Press Inc. All rights of any nature whatsoever reserved.
