699. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 38953891
ID  - 15262299 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15262299]
T1  - Glitazones and the management of insulin resistance: What they do and how might they be used
A1  - Einhorn D.
A1  - Aroda V.R.
A1  - Henry R.R. 
Y1  - 2004//
N2  - Thiazolidinediones (glitazones) are the only compounds currently available that specifically target tissue insulin resistance. The glitazones are highly selective and potent synthetic agonists for the nuclear receptor peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma (PPARgamma). By activating PPARgamma, the glitazones regulate genetic transcription and translation of numerous proteins, including many that are involved in glucose and lipid metabolism [1]. The two drugs in this class that are currently available and approved by the Food and Drug Administration for the treatment of type 2 diabetes mellitus (T2DM) only are pioglitazone (Actos) and rosiglitazone (Avandia). The therapeutic potential of the glitazones for other consequences of insulin resistance has stirred considerable interest, especially with regard to their potential beneficial impact on atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease (CVD) and T2DM prevention. They also have been considered in the management of polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS), nonalcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD), and other consequences of insulin resistance. The nonglycemic potential of glitazones is a clinical area in rapid evolution, wherein most data are on the impact of the glitazones on surrogate markers that are associated with diseases, not on disease outcomes. Several clinical outcome studies, however, will be completed in the next few years, which may shed light on how to optimally use the glitazones beyond their role in T2DM. This article provides insight and guidance to clinicians on the diverse nonglycemic potential of glitazones until conclusive outcome data become available.
